{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The internal physical state view (the internal state view for short) is the first alternative we will consider.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Instead of holding that experiences are relations to non-physical sense data created by neural states, this view holds that experiences are identical with neural states themselves.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Changes in the character of experience just are changes in neural states.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Internal physical state view: every sensory-perceptual experience with a certain character is necessarily identical with an 'internal' physical property, as it might be, a complex neural pattern.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "This property is an intrinsic property of the brain; it is not a relation to anything outside the brain.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Differences in the character of experience consist in differences in such intrinsic physical-properties of subjects.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "The internal state view is the polar opposite of 'naïve realism'.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "On naïve realism, the explanation for the character of your experiences resides primarily in your relations to the external world.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "On the internal state view, the character of your experiences is entirely constituted by the character of your internal neural processes.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The argument for the internal state view to be examined in this section has two steps.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The first step will argue for the general thesis 'experiential internalism': every aspect of the phenomenological character of our experiences is directly and fully determined by our neural states.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "This rules out 'naïve realism'.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "The second step will use additional considerations to argue that, between these options, the internal physical state view is to be preferred.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The sense datum view is a dualistic theory which holds that our internal neural states generate non-physical sense data that reside in private mental spaces.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "The internal state view eliminates this extra step.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "It directly identifies experiences with our internal neural states.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "It is therefore simpler and less mysterious than the sense datum view.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "The internal state view is inconsistent with the essentially externally directed character of some types of experiences.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Essential External Directedness: Some types of visual experiences essentially involve the seeming presence of items with certain shapes and other spatial features.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "They are essentially as of such items.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "This is so whether they are veridical or hallucinatory.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "For instance, having the orange-experience essentially involves the seeming-presence of a round thing that moves to the right.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "The argument from essential external directedness against the internal state view is a simple logical rule called Leibniz's law.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "This rule states that if what is true of A is not true of B, then A ≠ B.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "The argument says that different things are true of types of experiences and types of neural states, so they cannot be literally one and the same.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "A correct definition of what it is to have the orange-experience will include the spatial terms round and moves to the right.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "This is not true of the underlying neural state N.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU28": {
      "text": "It is not the case that a correct definition of neural state N will include the spatial terms round and moves to the right.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU29": {
      "text": "Therefore, having the orange experience is not identical with underlying neural state N, even if it may be dependent on that neural state.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU30": {
      "text": "The internal physical state view and essential external directedness together entail that brains simply have an innate, intrinsic capacity to mentally represent shapes and other perceptible properties.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU31": {
      "text": "This is somewhat mysterious.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU32": {
      "text": "David Papineau (2014, 2016) is a proponent of the internal physical state view who does exactly that: he rejects the essential external directedness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU33": {
      "text": "In this way, he avoids the problems raised in the previous sections for the internal state view based on external directedness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU34": {
      "text": "Papineau accepts premise (2): neural patterns don't essentially involve spatial features like round and moving to the right in any way.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU35": {
      "text": "To block the argument, he denies premise (1), that is, essential external directedness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU36": {
      "text": "He denies that such spatial features essentially enter into the characterization of our visual experiences.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU37": {
      "text": "He thinks that visual experiences are like neural patterns in that spatial features like round and moving to the right do not essentially enter into their characterization.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
